        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-01-07T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-01-07T18:00:00-05:00" n="499" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d499">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/1–749: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Consul General at Peiping</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Clubb</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-01-07T18:00:00-05:00">January 7, 1949—6 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>8. Dept requests info Fu Tso-yi’s<note n="6" xml:id="d499fn6">Commander in Chief
                        of the North China Bandit Suppression Headquarters.</note> disposition US
                    arms delivered Nov from CinCFE.<note n="7" xml:id="d499fn7">Commander in Chief,
                        Far East (MacArthur).</note> Were arms retained Peiping–Tientsin area or
                    sent west?</p>
                <p>Dept interested ConGen’s estimate whether food stocks Peiping and possible
                    channels supply would enable city endure extended investment.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lovett</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
